  "prompt": "Can myopia be cured?",
  "response": "As of now, myopia (nearsightedness) cannot be completely cured, but there are various treatment options available to manage and correct it. Common options include:\n\n1. **Eyeglasses**: Prescription lenses are the most common way to correct myopia, allowing individuals to see distant objects more clearly.\n\n2. **Contact Lenses**: Soft or rigid gas-permeable contact lenses can also correct myopia, often offering a wider field of vision compared to glasses.\n\n3. **Orthokeratology (Ortho-K)**: This involves wearing specially designed rigid gas-permeable contact lenses overnight to temporarily reshape the cornea, allowing clear vision during the day without corrective lenses.\n\n4. **Refractive Surgery**: Procedures like LASIK (Laser-Assisted In Situ Keratomileusis) and PRK (Photorefractive Keratectomy) use lasers to reshape the cornea, potentially reducing dependence on glasses or contact lenses.\n\n5. **Atropine Eye Drops**: Low-dose atropine drops have been used to slow the progression of myopia in children.\n\nWhile these methods can significantly improve vision and sometimes reduce myopia progression, none of them completely \"cure\" the condition in the sense of reversing the structural changes in the eye that cause myopia. Ongoing research continues to explore new treatments and potential cures. Always consult with an eye care professional for the most appropriate options based on individual needs.",
